147
00:13:01,060 --> 00:13:01,520
Yeah.

148
00:13:01,520 --> 00:13:04,800
So participatory budgeting is...

149
00:13:04,800 --> 00:13:07,740
It would be lovely if it was seen on a national scale.

150
00:13:07,740 --> 00:13:12,020
I have never seen anyone do it at that scale or for a whole budget.

151
00:13:12,120 --> 00:13:13,380
It's really...

152
00:13:13,380 --> 00:13:15,420
The take up of it has been...

153
00:13:15,420 --> 00:13:22,100
It is about spending public money, and it is about involving community citizens, people.

154
00:13:22,100 --> 00:13:26,740
Sometimes we don't use the word citizens, because there's an assumption that they have got the paperwork.

155
00:13:26,740 --> 00:13:32,380
Also, using ordinary people to make a decision about where a budget is spent.

156
00:13:32,380 --> 00:13:34,240
It came out of Brazil.

157
00:13:34,240 --> 00:13:38,240
It's been taken up quite widely in Europe, particularly in the UK.

158
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:40,720
There's been very little proper take up of it.

159
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,020
There's not a lot of take up of it in Australia.

160
00:13:44,020 --> 00:14:03,580
In the UK, there's a very strong, and probably in South America, that people need to turn up to a place that you come along and as a group of people together, you look at all the different ways people want to spend a budget, and then you talk about that and vote on that in a face-to-face process.

161
00:14:03,580 --> 00:14:12,680
There is a tech version of it where it's done online, and that has had a little bit of take-up in Australia.

162
00:14:12,680 --> 00:14:20,780
So the biggest project I know is the Victorian government's pick-my-project process that happened last year, where community groups could...

163
00:14:20,780 --> 00:14:22,460
There was a bucket of money.

164
00:14:22,460 --> 00:14:30,940
Community groups could seek to get some of that money, and everyone who was involved voted on where the money should go.

165
00:14:30,940 --> 00:14:33,100
But it was an online process.

166
00:14:33,100 --> 00:14:40,700
Melville Council in Western Australia has been doing a project, they call the Robin Hood Project, probably from the last five to six years.

167
00:14:40,700 --> 00:14:41,780
That's pretty fascinating.

168
00:14:41,780 --> 00:14:49,940
So it almost sounds like that participatory budgeting doesn't necessarily have to be for the nation, but it could even be for, say, a charity.

169
00:14:49,940 --> 00:14:52,560
Yes, it's far more typical for...

170
00:14:53,120 --> 00:14:55,960
Most local councils have a community grants program.

171
00:14:55,960 --> 00:14:59,560
It is much more focused on topics like that.

172
00:14:59,560 --> 00:15:03,620
I haven't seen anyone seriously talk about budgets.

173
00:15:03,860 --> 00:15:13,400
Some people would say that the City of Melbourne's 10-year financial plan deliberation was a participatory budgeting process because it was a deliberation around a budget.

174
00:15:13,400 --> 00:15:17,040
I would say it was a deliberation, not a PV process.

175
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:18,660
